Combined Risk Index Report for Micronesia

Combined Risk Index Explanation

The Combined Risk Index is calculated by normalizing the values of the following columns:

  • Rainfall in driest quarter: Lower value indicates higher risk
  • Elevation less than 10m: Lower value indicates higher risk
  • Flood Risk: Lower value indicates higher risk

Each column is normalized to a range between 0 and 1, where 0 represents the lowest risk and 1 represents the highest risk. The Combined Risk Index is the average of these normalized values.

Note that for the normalization:

  • Elevation values above 10m are set to 10m to account for high altitude outliers.
  • Flood Risk values above 10 are set to 10 to account for outliers.
  • Rainfall in driest quarter values above 800 are set to 800 to account for outliers.

In the Pacific context, these variables are crucial due to their direct impact on communities' vulnerability to natural disasters, accessibility, and overall resilience:

  • Rainfall in driest quarter: Reflects precipitation of driest quarter, essential for understanding drought risks.
  • Elevation less than 10m: Elevation is critical in assessing flood and storm surge risks. Lower elevations are more vulnerable.
  • Flood Risk: Directly measures the susceptibility to flooding events, a significant hazard in the Pacific.
High Risk Sites Classification

High risk sites are classified as follows:

  • Rainfall in driest quarter: Sites with values below 400mm.
  • Elevation: Sites with values below 5m.
  • Flood Risk: Sites with values below 5.

The percentage of high-risk sites is calculated as the number of high-risk sites divided by the total number of sites.

Methodology

Methodology Documentation

Rainfall in driest quarter: Data sourced from WORLDCLIM, calculated using precipitation of the driest quarter.

Elevation: Data sourced from MERIT Hydro DEM, calculated using elevation values.

Flood Risk: Data sourced from MERIT Hydro DEM, calculated using height above nearest drainage (HAND).
